Current Implementation Status — Project ECHO / CANDLE-01

Project ECHO has moved beyond conceptual architecture and is now entering the early private implementation stage through the CANDLE-01 reference environment.

The public repository continues to describe the doctrine, trust model, architectural shape, and safety principles of ECHO. The private CANDLE-01 environment is now being used to test how those principles translate into a working local-first command structure.

Current Development Stage

ECHO/CANDLE-01 is currently in a private prototype implementation phase.

The system now has early working components for:

local command routing
tool registration
command validation
dry-run dispatch testing
safety-rule scaffolding
safety-kernel enforcement testing
append-only execution logging
lightweight local memory/state persistence
developer handoff documentation
milestone-based implementation planning

These components are being built and tested privately as part of the CANDLE-01 reference implementation.

What Has Been Implemented Privately

The private implementation currently includes the first version of a local command spine:

Operator command
→ routing registry
→ dispatcher
→ safety check
→ dry-run or approved execution path
→ structured logging
→ local state/memory update where appropriate

This is not yet a production system, but the core implementation pattern is now present.

The current build demonstrates that ECHO’s public doctrine can be translated into practical system behavior:

commands are registered before use
commands can be validated against a registry
disabled or unknown commands can be blocked
safety rules are checked before execution
command activity can be logged
memory/state can persist locally
test paths can run without live execution
system behavior can be inspected after the fact
Current Maturity Level

At this stage, the implementation should be described as:

Private working prototype / early reference implementation

A more precise label would be:

CANDLE-01 Reference Implementation — Phase 1: Command Spine Prototype

The current build is not being presented as complete, commercial-ready, or externally deployable. It is a controlled private implementation used to validate ECHO’s architecture under real local operating conditions.

What This Proves

The current prototype shows that ECHO is not only a written framework.

It now has a developing operational structure capable of supporting:

deterministic tool routing
local-first execution boundaries
safety-first command gating
operator-controlled workflows
structured audit trails
early continuity across sessions
future integration with n8n, local AI retrieval, dashboards, and workflow automation

In plain terms:

The doctrine is public. The private reference implementation has begun proving the command, safety, logging, and memory spine.

What Is Not Public

The following remain private and are not included in the public repository:

private kernel logic
command dispatcher internals
safety-rule implementation details
memory implementation details
command maps
trust tables
local folder paths
private workflow logic
n8n workflow internals
implementation scripts
sensitive operational data

The public repository describes the shape and principles of ECHO. The private implementation contains the operational machinery.

Public-Safe Summary

Project ECHO is currently transitioning from public architectural doctrine into a private working reference implementation through CANDLE-01.

The first implementation layer now includes a local command spine with early routing, validation, safety gating, logging, dry-run testing, and local state persistence. This confirms that the ECHO model can move from theory into a practical local-first operating environment while preserving the core principles of human control, deterministic execution, safety boundaries, and auditability.

The implementation remains private, experimental, and under operator control. Public materials continue to expose only the architecture, doctrine, and trust model — not the internal execution machinery.
